Introduction

Fair division is a problem with roots in the Bible and in Greek mythology. When Abraham and Lot must divide the land of Canaan fairly among themselves, one divides the land into two parts (which they perceive to be equally valuable), and the other chooses their favorite piece. This problem has proven to be useful in practice. It has been used for international dispute resolution (Brams 2019), distribution of food for food banks, and estate divisions (Aleksandrov et al. 2015; Mertzanidis, Psomas, and Verma 2024; Caragiannis et al. 2019). This was formalized by (Steinhaus 1948) for both divisible continuous and indivisible discrete goods. Since then, several promising results have been published in both settings, with the existence of a bounded-time envy-free cake cutting procedure being resolved by (Aziz and Mackenzie 2017). However, the fair allocation of a finite set of indivisible goods to individuals "fairly" remains a fundamental open question within computer science and economics. Indeed, many interpretations of fairness exist. In this paper, we survey some common notions of fairness, their computability, and open questions within the field of Fair Division. We also present a small result connecting two notions of fairness (MNW and EQX).

Envy

Arguably, the gold standard of fair division is envy freeness (EF), where no agent would like another's bundle more than their own. Formally, . If this is not the case, (i.e. ), is said to "envy" "j". It is clear that for discrete goods, this does not always exist, as seen in the following counterexample:

Worse still, computing if an arbitrary instance admits an EF allocation is NP-complete (Lipton et al. 2004).

Thus, when allocating a finite set of goods, EF is relaxed to envy-freeness up to X (EFX) by allowing the removal of an arbitrary good from another agent's bundle such that for all .

For two agents, EFX can be computed using a variation of the "cut-and-choose" procedure. The first agent divides into two bundles, and such that they value each of them as near to as possible. Then, the second agents chooses the bundle which gives her higher utility, breaking ties arbitrarily. The second agent clearly does not envy the first, as they received the bundle with the highest valuation in their eyes. If the first agent prefers the bundle they received, we are done. Otherwise, the first agent cannot envy the second after the removal of a good, as otherwise this bring the valuation of the bundles closer to , which would contradict that the first agent selected as near to as they could initially. For three agents, (Chaudhury, Garg, and Mehlhorn 2024) showed that EFX can be computed as well in pseudo-polynomial time. (Akrami et al. 2022) later gave a simpler algorithm for this using casework to iteratively improve the allocation.

Thus, we come to our first open question.

The leximin solution is one which maximizes the minimum utility, then maximizing the second least utility, and so on. The leximin++ is the leximin solution, which, after maximizing the value of the bundle with minimum utility, maximizes size of the bundle. Then, maximizes the size of the second least agent's utility subject to maximizing the size of the second bundle and so on.

Although computing EFX for general additive valuations remains an open problem, several relaxations of EFX have been proposed which are easier to compute.

One natural easy-to-compute notion relaxation of EFX is EF1. Rather than allowing the removal of an arbitrary good, this is relaxed so that there must exist a good which can each be removed in order to resolve envy. In other words, for a good . This notion was first formally defined by (Budish 2011). Note that this is equivalent to removing the good which values the most in 's bundle to enforce envy-freeness , with . For general valuations, EF1 can be computed efficiently using simple polynomial time algorithms.

Maintain a "bag", and keep adding arbitrary goods until an agent values the bag at least , breaking ties arbitrarily. Once such an agent is found, add all the goods in the bag to and remove them from . When a single agent remains, give her the remaining unallocated goods.

(Procaccia and Wang 2014) first showed the existence of -MMS approximation algorithms. Despite the progress made in computing approximations, the approximation of MMS is incomplete. (Feige, Sapir, and Tauber 2022) showed a counterexample, showing that MMS allocations cannot always be approximated higher than , even for 3 agents.

Maximum Nash Welfare

Maximum Nash Welfare (MNW) is a more "global" notion of welfare. Namely, it considers the utility of each agent rather than agents' value over others'. This first maximizes the number of agents receiving positive utility, then maximizes the geometric mean of utilities. Let represent the set of all partitions of a set S into k elements. The MNW allocation is given by .

In the notion of the geometric mean, under identical additive valuations, this is maximized when all agents with positive utilities have valuations which are as similar as possible (after maximizing the agents with positive utilities). This is quite useful, as MNW provides strong guarantees for other notions of fairness.

(Caragiannis et al. 2019) also showed that a MNW allocation is guaranteed to be -MMS.

These guarantees however do not extend much further. (Amanatidis et al. 2021a) show that MNW does not give an EFX allocation in general, MNW is NP-hard even for identical additive valuations (Roos and Rothe 2010), although under binary and bi-valued (where ) instances it can be computed in polynomial time (Barman, Krishnamurthy, and Vaish 2018a). For 3-value instances, where , the problem of computing a MNW allocation is NP-complete (Amanatidis et al. 2021b). Thus, due to its hardness to compute, we seek to guarantee these properties without computing them through MNW.

As computing MNW allocations is APX-hard, thus prior research has sought to approximate MNW allocations for its desiderata. Can an EF1 and PO allocation be computed in polynomial time? For bounded valuations, (Barman, Krishnamurthy, and Vaish 2018b) develop a polynomial time algorithm, and in pseudo-polynomial time for general valuations.

EQX

Another notion of fairness based on utilities is EQX. An equitable (EQ) allocation is one in which all agent utilities are roughly the same. , however like EFX, this clearly does not exist. This motivates a similar relaxation, by allowing the removal of a good . EQX is well studied in the literature for both goods and for chores, and unlike EFX, is fairly easy to compute.

For identical valuations, EFX coincides with EQX, both of which can be computed efficiently. For strictly positive valuations, an EQX + PO allocation always exists, and an EQ1 + PO allocation can be found in pseudo-polynomial time (Freeman et al. 2019).

(Barman et al. 2024) shows that for all chores or all goods, EQX exists even for monotone allocations, and can be computed in polynomial time, although this is not true for arbitrary valuations (unless P=NP).

Between EFX and EF1

EFL (Envy-Freeness up to a Less Preferred Good) is meant to be “in-between” EFX and EF1. For agents and , rather than allowing the removal of an arbitrary good from , it only allows the removal of goods which are less valuable to than . In other words for and . This can be computed in polynomial time using envy-cycle elimination.

Randomness

Another line research focuses on randomness in fairness allocations.

EFR

(Farhadi et al. 2021) introduced the notion of envy-freeness up to a random good (EFR), where the expected envy of towards an agent can be eliminated. (Farhadi et al. 2021) also show that a -EFR allocation can be computed in polynomial time. However, such a mechanism cannot be strategyproof and envy free even in expectation (Basteck and Ehlers 2023).

Other EFX Notions

Epistemic EFX

(Aziz et al. 2018) proposed the notion of Epistemic Envy-Freeness where for each agent , the allocation can be made envy-free for by redistributing among . (Caragiannis et al. 2023) propose the slightly weaker notion of Epistemic EFX, defined similarly, but only requiring that the allocation can be made envy-free up to for . (Akrami and Rathi 2024) recently showed that EEFX allocations always exist and can be computed in polynomial time.

Charity

Although the existence of EX allocations is open, it always exists for a subset of goods. For example, trivially, the remoal of all goods yields and EFX allocation. The meaningful form of this is the idea of "charity", where a set of goods remain unallocated (i.e. “donated” to charity), and no agent should envy charity. (Chaudhury et al. 2021) give a polynomial time algorithm which donates at most goods to charity. (Berger et al. 2021) improve this to donating goods, and give an algorithm which donates only 1 good in the case of 4 agents.

Note that if an EFX allocations with 0 goods may be donated to charity exists, this is simply an EFX allocation.

(Akrami, Rezvan, and Seddighin 2022) propose a similar notion called EFkX, in which the removal of 2 goods from another agents' bundle rather than just one (i.e. EF1X is the same as EFX). They show the existence of EF2X allocations for restricted additive valuations (where ). note that an EFX allocation with charity can be turned into an EF2X allocation by giving the goods to unique agents.

Different Setting

Online Fair Division

While in the traditional model of fair division, items are assumed to be standard, agents and/or goods may arrive in an online manner. (Aleksandrov and Walsh 2020) survey online fair division in depth. Here, either agents, goods,or both arrive online at times . One approach to online fairness mechanisms is to asymptotically allocate goods such that envy the envy-per-good tends to 0, where is the maximum envy one agent has. (Benade et al. 2018) show that randomly allocating goods removes the expected envy. More interestingly, it is impossible to do better than such a mechanism, which is optimal up to a logarithmic factor. Online fair division however is not unilaterally easy to compute. (Aleksandrov and Walsh 2019) show that an ex-ante envy free (i.e. envy-free in expectation) and PO allocation may not always exist.

Chores and Mixed Manna

When all goods are chores, i.e. , the problem of fair division becomes much more difficult, and leads to several open problems. EFX for chores does not exist, and indeed is NP-complete to compute (Christoforidis and Santorinaios 2024). Should such an allocation exist, it is mutually exclusive from PO (Barman, Narayan, and Verma 2023). It also cannot have a finite approximation. Still, under the restricted context of bi-valued and binary valuations, EF1 and PO allocations exist (Ebadian, Peters, and Shah 2021; Barman, Narayan, and Verma 2023).

The division of goods with arbitrary valuations, where have shown several barriers for computation. For EQX allocations, (Barman et al. 2024) showed that EQX allocations are not guaranteed to exist, even under additive normalized valuations, and that determining if such an allocation exists is strongly NP-hard.

Incentives

Consider a setting with strategic agents. Here, an agent may misreport their valuations of goods in order to receive a better allocation. A strategyproof allocation is one in which such misreporting is not beneficial for such an agent.

Strategyproof mechanisms may not always exist while fulfilling the desiderata. (Caragiannis et al. 2009) show that in the context of strategic agents, an EFX allocation may not exist. (Amanatidis, Birmpas, and Markakis 2016) showed that no truthful mechanism could output an -MMS allocation for . Indeed, overall truthful mechanisms (Amanatidis et al. 2017) are incompatible allocations for general valuations.

For some restricted contexts, however, this can be done. Namely for binary valuations, computing an MNW and Lorenz-dominating allocation (and thus trivially a PO and EF1) allocation are strategyproof. (Halpern et al. 2020; Babaioff, Ezra, and Feige 2021) both develop algorithms to compute such allocations. They further show that under binary valuations, and even submodular valuations, a truthful mechanism exists to compute EFX allocations.

Proportionality

One of the earliest notions of fairness it that of proportionality (PROP), where each good values their allocation at least . Clearly, like envy-freeness, it cannot be guaranteed int he case of discrete goods, so it is necessary to weaken it slightly by allowing the addition of goods. In proportionality up to 1 good (PROP1), there exists a good where . Similarly, in proportionality up to x (PROPx), all goods where .

(Conitzer, Freeman, and Shah 2017) showed that a PROP1 and PO allocation always exists and can be computed in polynomial time.

Still proportionality can be disappointing, as (Aziz, Moulin, and Sandomirskiy 2020) showed that even for simple cases, a PROPx allocation may not exist.

An intermediary notion, PROPm has been shown to always exist and be computable in polynomial time. (Baklanov et al. 2021) defines the maximin good as is the largest among the smallest goods in other agent's bundles. If adding this good's value to 's utility is greater than or equal to , i.e. , then an allocation is PROPm.

Fisher Markets

Although Nash Welfare is compelling, for its simultaneous EF1 + PO, it is also NP-hard to compute. One line of work attempting to simultaneous achieve fairness and efficiency tries to use the computation of market equilibria of fisher markets. This has also been used to compute approximate MNW, as mentioned previously. In the fisher market, goods are given prices , agents are given earnings , and monotone valuations, as defined above. Although this remains an open question, prior work seeks to compute an approximate -CEEI allocation. In such an allocation, agents may spend for some .

Some work has been dedicated to computing approximations for CEEI. (Boodaghians, Chaudhury, and Mehta 2022) computes a -CEEI allocation with running time proportional to . (Chaudhury et al. 2022) gives an algorithm to compute a -CEEI in polynomial time for .

A fractionally Pareto optimal allocation (fPO) is a fractional allocation which is not Pareto-dominated by another fractional allocation. It is clear that an fPO allocation is PO, but not necessarily vice versa.

CEEI is compelling in computing fPO. (Mas-Colell, Whinston, and Green 1995) show that a CEEI is also fPO, and thus PO.

Empirical Results

We can see the practical usefulness of these results from prior experimental results. For discrete fair division, (Hosseini et al. 2023) collected a set of items, and computed an EF1 allocation among they agents. They then allowed agents to swap, and found that agents preferred to swap their bundles with other agents in of allocations.

Another common approach to allowing measurement of goods is to give each agent some number of "points", and allow them to distribute the points among the goods based on their preference, which for can still maintain the fairness properties of MNW and EF1. In Spliddit, for 1000 points and 10 agents, an MNW (EF1 and PO) allocation is computed in less than 3 seconds (Caragiannis et al. 2019; Dupuis-Roy and Gosselin 2009).

Discussion

In this survey, we discussed some of the most common notions of fairness. Although there are some further related notions of fairness, these are the most well-studied among the literature. We also showed that, under identical additive valuations, .

Related to fair division, within economics and computation (EC), recent research has also studied computing market equilibria, beyond the Fisher Market. Other works in EC focus more on strategyproofness, studying voting and consensus procedures.
